<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0311 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1350EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv27   05-25 0662</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 27,0693</SECOND><NOTE>$adv27</NOTE><NOTE>For release Fri AMs May 27, and thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Baptist television preachers disagreedover whether scandal-toppled TV preachers Jimmy Swaggart and JimBakker should be allowed to return to television preaching.   The Rev. James Robison of Dallas, speaking on an ABC newsprogram, argued that through forgiveness the gospel offers ``wholeand total restoration on the platform and in the pulpit.''   However, the Rev. Jerry Falwell of Lynchburg, Va., said clergyhave special responsibilities and ``we don't have the luxury of amajor, scandalous sin, and then going back into the pulpit.''   Robison said he has been counseling with Bakker and his wife,Tammy, and ``I think we're going to see a miracle in the lives oftwo people I once despised. I want to see them restored. I lovethem.''   Both Bakker and Swaggart were ousted from their TV operationsafter sex episodes, but Swaggart defied his denomination's ordersto stay off the air for a year.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Donna Hanson, the Catholic lay woman of Spokane,Wash., who addressed Pope John Paul II on his visit last fall andurged fuller attention to women's concerns, has been awarded theU.S. Catholic Award by the national magazine, U.S. Catholic.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The president of the United Church of Christhas urged the U.S. Congress to enact comprehensive economicsanctions against South Africa, citing indications that neighboringAfrican states favor such action.   The Rev. Avery D. Post, who led a delegation to that region inApril, told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that church andgovernment leaders in Angola, Zambia, Zimbabwe and Botswana wanttougher U.S. action against South Africa's system of racialseparation.   ``Our discussions gave evidence of a clear consensus ... thatthe kid-glove policy of the Reagan Administration toward SouthernAfrica has been misguided and counterproductive,'' Post said.</TEXT><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 11,000 Southern Baptist women filledthe Richmond Coliseum with pageantry and celebration May 13-14,marking the 100th anniversary of the Woman's Missionary Union.   The 1.2-million-member organization over the years has raised$1.2 billion to support missionary work.</TEXT><DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A monitoring organization says thataccording to a report from Hong Kong, three Jesusit priests held inprison in China for seven years have been released.   The U.S. offfice of Keston College, which keeps check onreligion in Communist countries, said the three _ the Revs. FrancisXavier Caio Shifang, Michael Qian Shengguan and Stanislaus YanYunliang _ are in addition to three Roman Catholic prisonersreleased last winter.</TEXT><DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Religion Newswriters Association has voiceddismay that U.S. Roman Catholic bishops have decided to discusstheir conflict over their AIDS statement in secret.   Review of the statement, assailed by conservative bishopsbecause it allows teaching about condoms in public school AIDSeducation, was scheduled at a meeting June 24-27 in Collegeville,Minn.   Ed Briggs of the Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch, president of theRNA, sent its protest in letter to Archbishop John May of St.Louis, president of Catholic bishops.   Expressing appreciation for ``the openness with which thebishops have conducted their meetings in recent years,'' Briggsasked reconsideration of the decision to hold the session on AIDSbehind closed doors.   ``Our fear is that the intense public interest and controversyover the AIDS statement has turned the conference back to itsprevious policy of secrecy,'' Briggs wrote.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Jewish official, commenting on Nancy Reagan'sreported consulting of an astrologer, says ``it is more than alittle scary to learn that occult superstition ... may beinfluencing'' the American government.   Rabbi Marc H. Tanenbaum, international relations director forthe American Jewish Committee, said in a WINS radio commentary:   ``From its ancient origins in Babylonia, astrology has beenregarded by most of the Western world's wisest minds as thehandmaiden of superstition and magical thinking.''</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, May 27</NOTE></DOC>